"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Romans chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-romans-1-3.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/romans.json
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (dikaiosyne, hilasterion, doulos, pistis)
- data/translation/notes/romans.json (translation reasoning)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/romans.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/echoes/romans.json (absorbed OT connections inform classification)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 1:1–17: opening apostolic identification and thesis — classified as theme/revelation of God
  with the thesis verses (1:16–17) receiving direct classification
- Ch 1:18–32: the moral descent — classified as revelation of God; the Fall backdrop
  is named but entries stay concise since typological content is thin in vice lists
- Ch 2: the diatribe against the impartial judge — revelation of God for most;
  2:16 (judgment through Christ) and 2:29 (heart-circumcision by Spirit) receive
  direct/fulfillment classification
- Ch 3:1–20: the catena of Scripture quotations — revelation of God; each OT quotation
  noted as scriptural witness to universal sin that Christ's work addresses
- Ch 3:21–31: the great disclosure — direct throughout; hilasterion (3:25) classified
  as fulfillment of the mercy-seat type from Lev 16 / Exod 25
- "Paul" used throughout (not "the Apostle")
- Directness levels stated in prose per guide: "A direct...", "A type:", "A shadow:",
  "A theme:", "A revelation of God:"
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ROMANS = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: Paul opens by defining himself as <em>doulos</em> — slave — of Christ Jesus before naming his apostolic office. The sequence matters: total ownership by Christ precedes and grounds the commission. The trajectory toward Christ shapes even the form of apostolic authority; Paul participates in a mission that belongs to Christ before it belongs to him.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct declaration: the gospel was "promised beforehand through his prophets in the Holy Scriptures." Paul frames the entire letter by insisting that what has occurred in Christ is not an interruption of Israel\'s covenant story but its fulfillment. The OT is not background material but the originating promise that the gospel brings to completion.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A fulfillment: "a descendant of David" grounds Christ\'s identity in the Davidic covenant of 2 Sam 7:12-13, where God promised a son of David whose kingdom would endure forever. Paul\'s opening verses establish the incarnation not as a generic divine entry into history but as the arrival of the promised Davidic heir — flesh and genealogy are theological, not merely biographical.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct declaration: the resurrection is the moment when Christ is "appointed the Son of God in power." The language echoes Ps 2:7 (the divine decree to the enthroned king: "You are my Son") and Ps 110:1 (the Lord\'s invitation to the Davidic king to sit at his right hand); Acts 13:33 and Heb 1:5 make the Ps 2 connection explicit. The resurrection is Christ\'s public enthronement — the moment when his identity as Son is confirmed before the world.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A fulfillment: the apostolic mission to bring "all the Gentiles to the obedience that comes from faith" is the realized form of the Isaianic Servant\'s commission to be "a light to the nations" (Isa 49:6). Paul understands his own vocation as participation in Christ\'s Servant-mission; the global scope of the gospel is not an expansion beyond Israel\'s categories but the arrival of what the prophets announced.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme: "called to belong to Jesus Christ" — the Roman believers\' identity is defined by belonging to a person. The calling-language (κλητοί, <em>klētoi</em>) echoes Israel\'s election — God\'s people are defined by divine initiative, not self-selection. In Christ, the category of God\'s elect people is extended to Gentiles in Rome without abandoning its covenantal shape.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "grace and peace from God our Father and from the Lord Jesus Christ" — the paired greeting places the Father and the Son as joint source of grace and peace, a Christological claim embedded in what reads as a conventional greeting. The peace Paul announces is not social or political but the eschatological <em>shalom</em> of the new covenant, now available through Christ.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: the worldwide report of the Roman church\'s faith is itself a sign of what the gospel has accomplished — the power of God reaching the imperial capital and producing a community of faith whose existence is itself public testimony. Christ\'s name is being declared wherever their faith is spoken of.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "God, whom I serve in my spirit in preaching the gospel of his Son" — Paul\'s worship is defined not by temple sacrifice but by gospel proclamation. The Servant of God\'s Son offers his service through speech, not blood. This represents the temple-worship pattern transposed into the apostolic mission Christ has inaugurated.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: Paul\'s prayer for an open door to Rome reflects the understanding that apostolic movement is subject to divine governance. The mission to the nations that Christ commissioned (Matt 28:19; Acts 1:8) proceeds under the Father\'s timing — Paul plans, God opens or closes the way.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "some spiritual gift to make you strong" — the strengthening Paul intends to impart is not a natural resource but a pneumatic one, flowing from the Spirit of Christ. The apostle functions as a conduit for the risen Christ\'s ongoing ministry of building up his people.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: mutual encouragement through shared faith is itself a Christological reality — it is "each other\'s faith" that encourages, not merely mutual goodwill. The faith that unites the community is faith in Christ; its encouragement is therefore an extension of what Christ produces in his people.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: Paul\'s mission strategy — seeking "a harvest" among the Gentiles — frames his apostolic work in the harvest-of-the-nations imagery that runs from Isa 27:12 through the prophets and into Jesus\' own teaching (Matt 9:37-38; John 4:35-38). The Gentile mission is not Paul\'s initiative but the completion of a trajectory the prophets anticipated.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A theme: "obligated both to Greeks and non-Greeks" — the obligation Paul names is not social but missional. Christ\'s death for all creates a debt of proclamation: the apostle owes the gospel to every people group precisely because the one who died did so for all. The universality of the atonement generates the universality of the mission.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: Paul\'s eagerness to preach in Rome — the heart of imperial power — reflects the Christ-shaped inversion of honor and shame. He is "not ashamed" (v16) to bring the gospel to the city where crucifixion-criminals are mocked; what Rome considers weakness, Paul declares to be the power of God.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct declaration: "the gospel is the power of God that brings salvation to everyone who believes: first to the Jew, then to the Gentile." Paul\'s thesis identifies the gospel not as information about Christ but as the actual vehicle of divine saving power — <em>dynamis theou</em> (power of God) is not metaphorical. The priority order (Jew first) reflects the historical-redemptive sequence: Christ came as Israel\'s Messiah; the Gentile mission flows from that.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct declaration: "the righteousness of God is revealed — a righteousness that is by faith from first to last." Paul cites Hab 2:4 ("the righteous will live by faith") as the scriptural key: what the prophet announced as the principle of covenant survival through the Babylonian crisis is now disclosed as the universal structure of life before God, fulfilled in Christ. The entire letter argues from this thesis.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "the wrath of God is being revealed from heaven against all the godlessness and wickedness of people." The backdrop for the gospel of righteousness (v17) is the revelation of wrath (v18) — both are present-tense revelations. The gospel is not good news abstracted from a problem; it is rescue from a condition Paul now proceeds to describe. Christ\'s atoning work (3:25) will be the answer to the wrath established here.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: natural revelation — "what may be known about God is plain to them, because God has made it plain to them." The witness of creation establishes universal accountability; no one stands outside the reach of God\'s self-disclosure. This universal culpability is the negative premise that makes Christ\'s rescue universally necessary.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "his eternal power and divine nature have been clearly seen, being understood from what has been made, so that people are without excuse." Creation\'s witness is sufficient to establish guilt — it cannot, Paul will argue, produce righteousness. The law of nature condemns; only the gospel justifies (3:21-26). The same God who made the world now discloses himself definitively in Christ.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "although they knew God, they neither glorified him as God nor gave thanks to him." The failure is not ignorance but refusal — a moral suppression rather than an epistemic gap. This root-condition (ungratitude and failure to glorify) is what the gospel reverses: in Christ, God is properly glorified in his people (Rom 15:9; 1 Cor 10:31).</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "although they claimed to be wise, they became fools." The wisdom-folly inversion here anticipates the logic of 1 Cor 1:18-25, where the cross — itself an apparent folly — is declared the wisdom of God. The world\'s wisdom that rejects the knowledge of God is the very foolishness that the gospel exposes.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A shadow: the exchange of "the glory of the immortal God for images" is the anti-type of the divine purpose in creation and salvation. Where idolatry degrades, the gospel restores: Paul will later speak of believers being "transformed into his image" (2 Cor 3:18) and of the glory of God being fully manifest in Christ (2 Cor 4:6). The exchange described here is what redemption reverses.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "God gave them over in the sinful desires of their hearts" — the triple <em>paredōken</em> ("gave them over," vv24, 26, 28) presents God\'s wrath not as arbitrary punishment but as the judicial form of allowing creation to follow its own rebellion to its consequences. The rescue from this condition is what Paul will identify in 5:8: "God demonstrates his own love for us in this: while we were still sinners, Christ died for us."</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "they worshiped and served created things rather than the Creator." The Creator–creature distinction, fundamental to OT theology and to Israel\'s covenant, is what all idolatry violates. Christ, whom Paul has just identified as the one through whom creation was ordered (by implication in the Davidic Son language of 1:3-4), is the one who re-establishes right relationship between Creator and creature.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "God gave them over to shameful lusts" — the second judicial handing-over reveals how moral disorder proliferates when the fundamental relationship to the Creator is broken. The disorder described is not merely a social problem but a symptom of the theological rupture at humanity\'s foundation, the rupture that only the gospel addresses.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: men "received in themselves the due penalty for their error" — the self-destructive consequence of departing from God\'s design is built into the disordering itself. Paul\'s moral argument is not moralistic; it is diagnostic. The purpose is not condemnation but to establish that the human condition requires rescue from outside, which the gospel provides.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "God gave them over to a depraved mind" — the third handing-over culminates in cognitive corruption. The mind that refuses to retain God becomes functionally disordered. This is the condition that Paul, in later letters, describes Christ\'s renewal reversing: "be transformed by the renewing of your mind" (12:2). The Christological answer to 1:28 is 12:2.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: the vice list beginning here is not rhetorical padding but evidence. Paul\'s argument requires that universal human sinfulness be demonstrated concretely; the list shows that the abstract claim of v18 ("all the godlessness and wickedness of people") has recognizable, specific contents. The universality of this condition is precisely what makes Christ\'s rescue necessary for everyone.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "God-haters, insolent, arrogant and boastful" — the social vices in the list trace back to the theological root of 1:21: failure to glorify God produces inversion in every human relationship. The gospel produces the opposite pattern: humility, truth, love — the character of Christ reproduced in those who are united to him.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "no understanding, no fidelity, no love, no mercy" — the four absences describe the collapse of the covenant virtues (faithfulness, steadfast love, mercy) that characterize God himself (Exod 34:6-7) and that he designed his image-bearers to reflect. Christ is the one who displays these perfectly and restores them in those who are in him (Col 3:12-14).</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "they not only continue to do these very things but also approve of those who practice them." The communal approval of what God\'s decree condemns is the deepest form of suppression described in 1:18-32 — not merely individual failure but a culture of consent to what God has declared deadly. This communal solidarity in sin is answered by a communal solidarity in grace: "in Christ" as the new corporate identity Paul will develop.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "you who pass judgment on someone else, for at whatever point you judge another, you are condemning yourself." The diatribe turns from the pagan to the moralist — whether Gentile philosopher or Torah-observant Jew. The logic is inexorable: one who judges by the same moral standard one violates provides the criteria for one\'s own condemnation. No one stands outside the need for the righteousness Christ provides.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "God\'s judgment against those who do such things is based on truth." The standard is not social convention or self-assessed virtue but the objective truth of who God is and what he requires. This grounding of judgment in divine truth is what makes the gospel of imputed righteousness the only solution — only a righteousness grounded in God\'s own truth can meet this standard.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "do you think you will escape God\'s judgment?" — rhetorical question to the moralizing judge who applies standards he himself fails. The assumption of exemption — whether through religious identity, moral effort, or ritual observance — is demolished here as preparation for the announcement that the only escape is through Christ (5:1-2: "justified through faith, we have peace with God").</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "God\'s kindness is intended to lead you to repentance." The patience of God is not indifference to sin but a summons — the classical OT characterization of God as slow to anger (Exod 34:6; Joel 2:13) is here given a teleological shape: divine forbearance aims at repentance. Paul will later argue that it is Christ\'s death that absorbs the wrath which patience deferred (3:25-26).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "the day of God\'s wrath, when his righteous judgment will be revealed" — the eschatological day of judgment that the prophets announced (Zeph 1:14-18) is here established as certain. Paul\'s letter moves between the present revelation of wrath (1:18) and its future eschatological completion; Christ\'s intercession (8:34) is what stands between the believer and that day.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "God will repay each person according to what they have done" — citing Ps 62:12 and Prov 24:12. Individual moral accountability before a perfectly just God is an axiom Paul affirms, not softens. The gospel does not abolish this principle but fulfills it: Christ bears what the repaid verdict requires for those united to him, so that the "repayment" of wrath falls on him rather than on them.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "to those who by persistence in doing good seek glory, honor and immortality, he will give eternal life." The category of those who actually do good consistently enough to inherit eternal life by that route is, Paul will demonstrate (3:10-12), empty. But the category itself is genuine: the standard is real. Christ is the only one who actually meets it, and by faith, those in him receive the verdict they could not earn.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: wrath and anger for those who "reject the truth and follow evil" — the judicial response to persistent truth-rejection is not arbitrary but proportionate to the gravity of suppressing what God has made plain (1:19-20). The revelation of wrath (1:18) is now given its concrete judicial content: future reckoning for sustained defection from truth.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "trouble and distress for every human being who does evil: first for the Jew, then for the Gentile." The priority order of 1:16 ("first to the Jew") applies equally to judgment: the covenant privilege that makes Israel\'s blessing first also makes Israel\'s accountability first. This is not anti-Jewish but covenantal — greater privilege entails greater accountability (Amos 3:2).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "glory, honor and peace for everyone who does good: first for the Jew, then for the Gentile." The symmetry with v9 reinforces Paul\'s point about God\'s impartiality: both the blessing and the curse of the Deuteronomic covenant apply universally. The ground of the promised "peace" (shalom) that Paul will announce in 5:1 ("we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ") is established here as something God gives — not something humanity produces.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "God does not show favoritism" — <em>prosōpolēmpsia</em> (partiality, literally "receiving of faces"). This principle, drawn from Deut 10:17, is foundational for Paul\'s argument that the gospel is for all without distinction (3:22-23). The impartial God who judges impartially also justifies impartially — "to all who believe" (3:22), regardless of ethnic or religious identity.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: those without the law perish apart from the law; those under it are judged by it. The universality of accountability is preserved across both tracks. This sets up the devastating point Paul is building to: no track — Gentile conscience or Jewish Torah — actually produces the righteousness God requires. Both tracks lead to the same conclusion: the need for what 3:21-24 provides.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "it is not those who hear the law who are righteous in God\'s sight, but it is those who obey the law who will be declared righteous." The standard is genuine obedience, not mere possession or knowledge. Paul will shortly demonstrate (3:9-18) that no one meets this standard — establishing that the "declaration of righteousness" must come from somewhere other than law-observance. Christ is the one who fully obeys and whose obedience is reckoned to faith (5:19).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: Gentiles who "do by nature things required by the law" demonstrate that the moral structure of God\'s law is not foreign to humanity but inscribed in it — the image of God (Gen 1:26-27) is not wholly erased. This partial witness anticipates the new covenant\'s full work: writing the law on the heart by the Spirit (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26-27), which Paul will later describe as fulfilled in those who walk by the Spirit (8:4).</p>',
    "15": '<p>A shadow: the law "written on their hearts" in conscience is a partial and unreliable anticipation of the new covenant promise of Jer 31:33, where God himself writes his law on the heart fully and effectively. Paul\'s language here deliberately echoes Jeremiah\'s new covenant passage; the conscience is the shadow, the Spirit\'s work in the new covenant is the substance. The shadow establishes accountability; the substance is what Christ\'s work makes possible.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct declaration: "the day when God judges people\'s secrets through Jesus Christ." The eschatological judgment — already established in vv5-6 — is here identified as mediated through Christ. The one who died for sinners is also the one who will judge them; the gospel and the judgment have the same Christ at their center. This is the only explicit mention of Christ in this chapter, placed at its structural climax: all of Paul\'s argument about sin and judgment converges on the one through whom God will adjudicate.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: the diatribe now addresses directly the Jew who relies on the law and boasts in God. Paul is not critiquing Jewish identity as such but the assumption that covenant privilege functions as a shield against the universal accountability he has established. The critique is the prophetic tradition\'s own (Mic 3:11; Jer 7:4): claiming God without corresponding obedience.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "you know his will and approve of what is superior because you are instructed by the law." The law\'s genuine advantage — giving knowledge of God\'s will — is acknowledged, not denied. But knowledge of the superior without corresponding practice deepens rather than reduces culpability. Paul will argue in ch7 that the law cannot produce what it reveals to be necessary.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "you are convinced that you are a guide for the blind, a light for those who are in the dark." Paul echoes the Isaianic Servant language (Isa 42:6-7) applied now to the Jewish teacher\'s self-understanding. The irony is severe: Israel was given the Servant\'s mission-language, but the Servant himself has now come and been rejected. The teachers of the blind are themselves blind (John 9:39-41).</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "instructor of the foolish, a teacher of little children, because you have in the law the embodiment of knowledge and truth." The law is genuinely the embodiment of knowledge and truth — Paul does not dispute this. But the one who possesses the embodiment while failing its demands is in a worse position than the one who never had it. Privilege is responsibility.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "you, then, who teach others, do you not teach yourself?" The rhetorical questions are from the prophetic tradition (Ps 50:16-21; Mic 3:11) — the gap between claimed identity and actual conduct is Israel\'s persistent failure, which the prophets indicted across centuries. Paul reprises the indictment not to condemn Israel uniquely but to establish that no ethnic or religious category provides exemption from the universal need for grace.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "you who say people should not commit adultery, do you commit adultery?" The questions intensify: stealing, adultery, robbing temples. The specific transgressions suggest Paul may be drawing on known patterns rather than rhetorical invention. The point is structural: moral knowledge without moral power is not righteousness but heightened condemnation. What is needed is not better instruction but a new nature — what Christ accomplishes through the Spirit.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "you who boast in the law, do you dishonor God by breaking the law?" Boasting in the law while breaking it is the precise form of self-deception Paul dismantles. The solution is not better law-keeping but the righteousness that comes through faith (3:22) — a righteousness external to the self, received rather than achieved, which is what the boasting of 3:27 will be excluded from claiming.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: Paul quotes Isa 52:5 LXX — "God\'s name is blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you." In Isaiah the charge falls on Israel in exile; Paul applies it to Torah-breaking Jews in the diaspora. The name of God, which Israel was called to make known among the nations, is dishonored by the conduct of those who bear it. Christ, in contrast, is the one through whom God\'s name is rightly glorified among the Gentiles (Rom 15:9).</p>',
    "25": '<p>A theme: "circumcision has value if you observe the law" — Paul engages the foundational covenant sign of Gen 17 not to abolish it but to expose the conditionality built into its own terms. Gen 17:14 specifies excision for the uncircumcised who breaks the covenant; circumcision without covenant-keeping is self-undermining. This argument prepares for the redefinition Paul will offer in vv28-29 and develop fully in ch4 (Abraham\'s faith before circumcision).</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "if those who are not circumcised keep the law\'s requirements, will they not be regarded as though they were circumcised?" The hypothetical raises the question of what circumcision actually signifies. Paul\'s answer will be Spirit-worked inner transformation (v29), which is the new covenant fulfillment of what the external sign always pointed toward. The uncircumcised Gentile who obeys by the Spirit exceeds the circumcised Jew who violates by the flesh.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "the one who is not circumcised physically and yet obeys the law will condemn you who, even though you have the written code and circumcision, are a lawbreaker." The possession of the external sign without the internal reality inverts the anticipated order of privilege and judgment. Paul\'s logic here anticipates the new covenant community: what matters is not the sign but the reality the sign was designed to represent.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "a person is not a Jew who is one only outwardly." Paul does not abolish Jewish identity but redefines its essence. The external markers — circumcision, law, ethnic descent — are not the core; they are the outer form of an inner reality. This prepares the radical claim of v29 and the redefinition of "Israel" that Paul will return to in chs 9-11.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A fulfillment: "circumcision is circumcision of the heart, by the Spirit, not by the written code." Paul explicitly fulfills the new covenant promise of Jer 31:33 ("I will put my law in their minds and write it on their hearts") and the Deuteronomic demand of Deut 30:6 ("the Lord your God will circumcise your hearts"). What Moses foresaw and Jeremiah promised, the Spirit of Christ effects in those who believe. The "true Jew" is defined by the Spirit\'s work — the eschatological fulfillment has arrived.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "what advantage, then, is there in being a Jew?" Paul\'s diatribal partner raises the obvious objection: if moral failure is universal and external circumcision ultimately inadequate, why does Israel\'s election matter? Paul will not dismiss the question — Jewish privilege is real (v2), and the entire structure of redemptive history runs through Israel\'s covenant with God, culminating in Israel\'s Messiah.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "the Jews have been entrusted with the very words of God." The advantage is specific and historical: Israel was the custodian of the divine oracles — the Torah, the prophets, the promises. This custodianship was not ethnic superiority but covenant stewardship. The oracles they held contained the gospel Paul now preaches (1:2: "promised beforehand through his prophets in the Holy Scriptures").</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "will their unfaithfulness nullify God\'s faithfulness?" The question is whether Israel\'s covenant failure can undo the divine commitment. Paul\'s answer will be a consistent no — divine faithfulness does not depend on human faithfulness. This principle is the ground of the gospel: God\'s righteousness is revealed "apart from the law" (3:21) precisely because human law-keeping has failed as a vehicle of covenant faithfulness.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "let God be true, and every human being a liar." Paul cites Ps 51:4 — David\'s penitential confession that God is vindicated in his judgment. The universal acknowledgment of human guilt and divine truthfulness is the baseline reality Scripture itself establishes. The gospel does not create this condition; it answers it: Christ is the one who takes the verdict ("just") and makes the sinner "justified" (3:26).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "if our unrighteousness brings out God\'s righteousness more clearly, what shall we say?" The diatribal objector floats the antinomian conclusion: if sin showcases divine righteousness, is God unjust to punish it? Paul labels this a "human argument" — it reasons from the effect (divine glory revealed through sin) to a conclusion (sin is therefore acceptable) that confuses God\'s capacity to bring good from evil with divine approval of evil. Christ\'s death, not ongoing sin, is what demonstrates God\'s righteousness (3:25-26).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "certainly not! If that were so, how could God judge the world?" The right of God to judge the world — assumed throughout Scripture from Gen 18:25 onward — would be incoherent if sin were somehow divinely sanctioned. Paul\'s brief response preserves both divine righteousness and divine judgment as foundations that the gospel addresses rather than dissolves.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: the hypothetical objection intensifies — "if my falsehood enhances God\'s truthfulness... why am I still condemned as a sinner?" The argument exploits the genuine logic that God\'s glory is displayed through contrast with human failure. Paul\'s answer, given implicitly by the rhetorical force of v8, is that the logic collapses under its own weight: a God who could not condemn what increases his glory would be neither truthful nor just.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "why not say — let us do evil that good may result?" Paul names the antinomian slander as a known misrepresentation of his gospel. The charge that grace-teaching leads to moral license is not a later misreading but a first-century accusation. Paul\'s answer here is brief ("their condemnation is just"); his full answer is Romans 6, where union with Christ\'s death and resurrection is shown to be the death of sin\'s dominion, not its license.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jews and Gentiles alike are all under the power of sin." The Greek <em>hyph\' hamartian</em> ("under sin") is a power-language — sin is not merely a category of acts but a regime. This sets up the Christological resolution of ch5-8: what liberates from sin\'s dominion is not moral effort or covenant status but union with Christ, who has entered and broken sin\'s realm through his death (6:10: "the death he died, he died to sin once for all").</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "there is no one righteous, not even one" — Paul opens his OT catena with Ps 14:1-3 (cf. Ps 53:1-3). The psalm surveys humanity from God\'s perspective and returns the verdict of universal corruption. Paul wields it not as rhetoric but as Scripture\'s own testimony, closing off any Jewish exemption: the psalms are Israel\'s Scripture, and Israel\'s Scripture declares Israel equally under indictment.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "there is no one who understands; there is no one who seeks God." The continuation of the Ps 14 catena establishes that the failure is not merely moral but cognitive and volitional: understanding and seeking God — the two foundational religious capacities — are absent. This is the condition of humanity apart from divine initiative. The gospel is precisely that God sought those who were not seeking him (Rom 10:20, quoting Isa 65:1).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "all have turned away, they have together become worthless; there is no one who does good, not even one." The third line of the catena extends the verdict: defection is universal ("all"), social ("together"), and total ("not even one" exception). Paul is not arguing for misanthropy but for the necessity of what 3:21-24 provides: a righteousness that comes entirely from outside the human moral record.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: Paul adds Ps 5:9 ("their throats are open graves; their tongues practice deceit") and Ps 140:3 ("the poison of vipers is on their lips"). The organs of speech become the site of the indictment — what comes out of the human mouth reveals the condition of the heart. Jesus will make the same point (Matt 15:18-19). The universality of speech-corruption closes off the route of self-defense through verbal protest.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: Ps 10:7 — "their mouths are full of cursing and bitterness." The catena continues its anatomy of human corruption through speech: from open graves (v13) to cursing and bitterness (v14). Paul\'s accumulation is structural, not exhaustive; he selects texts that cover the full range of human faculties — throat, tongue, lips, mouth — to show the comprehensiveness of sin\'s reach.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: Isa 59:7-8 enters the catena — "their feet are swift to shed blood." Isaiah\'s indictment of Israel\'s corporate moral failure is now deployed by Paul as evidence not against Israel specifically but against humanity universally. The prophets who accused Israel are the same prophets whose words establish the universal verdict. Paul\'s catena thus uses Israel\'s own Scriptures to close every avenue of covenant-exemption.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: continuing Isa 59:8 — "ruin and misery mark their paths." The consequences of the moral corruption catalogued in the catena are social destruction: ruin (<em>syntrimma</em>, brokenness) and misery. This is not merely individual but structural — the human project of building civilization is undermined by the condition sin produces. The gospel reverses this at its root, not merely at the level of improved behavior.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God and a theme: "the way of peace they do not know." The catena reaches its penultimate indictment with the absence of peace. The peace (<em>shalom</em>) that Israel\'s prophets promised as the mark of the coming kingdom (Isa 9:6; 52:7) is precisely what fallen humanity cannot produce or find. Paul will announce in 5:1 that "we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ" — the answer to the "way of peace they do not know."</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: Ps 36:1 closes the catena — "there is no fear of God before their eyes." The psalmist identifies the root beneath all the corruptions catalogued: the absence of the fear of God. Paul places this at the end as the theological summary of the preceding seven quotations. Every specific failure (speech, violence, social destruction) flows from this foundational defection. The beginning of wisdom — and the beginning of the gospel\'s reversal — is here.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "so that every mouth may be silenced and the whole world held accountable to God." The purpose of the law\'s indictment is universal accountability — not the conviction of a subset (Gentiles, or irreligious Jews) but every mouth, including the most observant. The courtroom imagery (silenced mouth, accountable world) establishes the forensic frame within which 3:21-26 will announce the verdict-reversal that the gospel provides.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "no one will be declared righteous in God\'s sight by the works of the law; rather, through the law we become conscious of our sin." The law\'s function is diagnostic, not curative — it reveals the disease without providing the remedy. Paul draws on Ps 143:2 ("no living person is righteous before you") and stands in tension with Lev 18:5 (life through doing): the life-through-doing route is foreclosed because no one actually does it fully. This verse is the negative premise that makes 3:21 ("but now") the hinge of the letter.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A direct declaration: "but now apart from the law the righteousness of God has been made known." <em>Nyni de</em> ("but now") is the most decisive temporal hinge in Romans — the shift from the long diagnosis of condemnation (1:18–3:20) to the announcement of rescue. The righteousness of God is not new — "the Law and the Prophets testify" to it (Isa 53:11; Isa 51:5-6) — but it has now been definitively disclosed and enacted in Christ\'s death and resurrection.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct declaration: "this righteousness is given through faith in Jesus Christ to all who believe. There is no difference between Jew and Gentile." The gospel\'s two revolutionary claims: the vehicle is faith in Christ (not law-observance), and the scope is universal (no distinction). The two claims are logically connected: because righteousness comes through Christ and not through the ethnic-covenantal marker of the law, it is available to all who trust him.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God." The "glory of God" fallen humanity fails to reach is the divine presence and honor that image-bearers were created to reflect (Gen 1:26-27) and that the Fall forfeited (Gen 3:23-24). The restoration of that glory is what the gospel accomplishes: "the glory of God in the face of Christ" (2 Cor 4:6); believers are being "transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory" (2 Cor 3:18).</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct declaration: "all are justified freely by his grace through the redemption that came by Christ Jesus." Three interlocking gifts: justification (the verdict of righteousness), grace (the basis — unmerited), and redemption (the mechanism — the liberation Christ accomplished). The term <em>apolytrōsis</em> (redemption) carries Exodus overtones (Exod 6:6) — Christ\'s work is the definitive new-exodus rescue from sin\'s bondage, the event all prior redemptions anticipated.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "God presented Christ as a <em>hilastērion</em> — a sacrifice of atonement through the shedding of his blood." The term <em>hilastērion</em> is precisely the LXX word for the <em>kapporeth</em> (the mercy seat, the golden cover of the ark) where atonement blood was applied on the Day of Atonement (Lev 16:14-16; Exod 25:17-22). Paul presents Christ as the fulfillment of this type: the locus where God and humanity meet, where blood is presented, where sin is covered. The structural correspondence (atoning blood, divine presence, covering of previously unpunished sin) is exact and deliberate.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct declaration: "so as to be just and the one who justifies those who have faith in Jesus." The apparent paradox of divine justice — how can the righteous God declare guilty sinners righteous? — is resolved at the cross. The <em>hilastērion</em> (v25) absorbs the wrath that justice required; the guilty are justified without injustice because judgment has fallen. Paul\'s climactic claim is that the gospel simultaneously upholds God\'s justice and extends his justifying mercy — a resolution Isa 45:21 anticipated but could not yet explain.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "where, then, is boasting? It is excluded." The gospel ends all grounds for human self-commendation before God. The "law of faith" (the principle that righteousness is received, not achieved) structures out the possibility of claiming credit. The appropriate response to the gospel is not pride but gratitude — the doxological character of the letter\'s later chapters (11:33-36; 15:5-13) follows directly from this exclusion.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct declaration: "a person is justified by faith apart from the works of the law." This is the letter\'s thesis distilled to its simplest form. Paul will spend chs4-5 arguing from Abraham and Adam; chs6-8 addressing the moral implications; chs9-11 addressing Israel\'s place in the plan. All of it unfolds from this declaration: justification is by faith in Christ, not by law-performance.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "or is God the God of Jews only? Is he not the God of Gentiles too?" The monotheism of the Shema (Deut 6:4) implies the universal scope of God\'s justifying work. One God means one standard of access — faith — for all peoples. The gospel is not a departure from Israel\'s theology but its logical extension: if God is truly the God of all creation, then his righteousness reaches all who believe, from every nation.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A direct declaration: "there is only one God, who will justify the circumcised by faith and the uncircumcised through that same faith." Monotheism generates the unity of the justifying method: one God, one means (faith), two covenant tracks (circumcised and uncircumcised) now unified in Christ. The Jew-Gentile distinction that structured redemptive history is not abolished but fulfilled — absorbed into the one people of God constituted by faith in Israel\'s Messiah.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "do we, then, nullify the law by this faith? Not at all! Rather, we uphold the law." The accusation that grace-faith destroys Torah is answered in two ways here: (1) the law itself testified to this righteousness (3:21), so faith vindicates the law\'s witness rather than undermining it; (2) in ch4, Paul will show that Abraham\'s justification by faith preceded and was confirmed by his circumcision. The law\'s deepest intention — to bring people into right relationship with God — is fulfilled by faith in Christ, not annulled.</p>'
  }
}

